#Read users data
users_data <- read.csv("C:/Users/DELL/Downloads/users_data.csv")

# Remove dollar signs and convert to numeric
users_data$per_capita_income <- as.numeric(gsub("\\$", "", users_data$per_capita_income))
users_data$yearly_income <- as.numeric(gsub("\\$", "", users_data$yearly_income))
users_data$total_debt <- as.numeric(gsub("\\$", "", users_data$total_debt))

library(ggplot2)

# Create a scatter plot
ggplot(users_data, aes(x = current_age, y = yearly_income, color = factor(cluster))) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +  # Use semi-transparent points
  labs(title = "Customer Segmentation by Age and Yearly Income",
       x = "Current Age",
       y = "Yearly Income",
       color = "Cluster") +
  theme_minimal() +  # Use a minimal theme for better aesthetics
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue", "green"))  # Custom colors for clusters

#Creating interactive map based on longitude and latitude including income and credit score
library(leaflet)
## Warning: package 'leaflet' was built under R version 4.4.2
# Create interactive map
leaflet(users_data) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    ~longitude, ~latitude,
    color = ~colorQuantile("YlOrRd", yearly_income)(yearly_income),
    popup = ~paste(
      "Income:", scales::dollar(yearly_income),
      "<br>Credit Score:", credit_score
    )
  )
#retirement_analysis based on gender
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
retirement_analysis <- users_data %>%
  mutate(
    years_to_retirement = retirement_age - current_age, #how many years left to retire
    retirement_year = birth_year + retirement_age       
  ) %>%
  group_by(gender) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_retirement_age = mean(retirement_age, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_years_to_retirement = mean(years_to_retirement, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_income = median(yearly_income, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

retirement_analysis
## # A tibble: 2  4

# Visualization for Average Retirement Age and Years to Retirement
ggplot(retirement_analysis, aes(x = gender)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = avg_retirement_age, fill = "Average Retirement Age"), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  geom_bar(aes(y = avg_years_to_retirement, fill = "Average Years to Retirement"), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Retirement Analysis by Gender",
       x = "Gender",
       y = "Years",
       fill = "Metric") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Average Retirement Age" = "lightblue", "Average Years to Retirement" = "salmon"))

# Financial health analysis based on given debt ratio and credit score
financial_health <- users_data %>%
  mutate(
    # Calculate the debt ratio
    debt_ratio = total_debt / yearly_income,
    # Assign a financial health score based on conditions
    financial_health_score = case_when(
      debt_ratio <= 0.3 & credit_score >= 750 ~ "Excellent",
      debt_ratio <= 0.4 & credit_score >= 700 ~ "Good",
      debt_ratio <= 0.5 & credit_score >= 650 ~ "Fair",
      TRUE ~ "Poor"  # All other cases are classified as "Poor"
    )
  ) %>%
  # Group the data by financial health score
  group_by(financial_health_score) %>%
  summarise(
    count = n(),  # Count of users in each financial health category
    avg_income = mean(yearly_income, na.rm = TRUE),  # Average income for each category
    avg_debt = mean(total_debt, na.rm = TRUE),  # Average debt for each category
    avg_credit_score = mean(credit_score, na.rm = TRUE)  # Average credit score for each category
  )

# Display the financial health analysis
financial_health

# Visualization: Count of Users and Average Income
ggplot(financial_health, aes(x = financial_health_score)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = count, fill = "Count of Users"), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +  # Bar for count of users
  geom_line(aes(y = avg_income / 1000, group = 1, color = "Average Income (in thousands)"), size = 1) +  # Line for average income, scaled down
  geom_point(aes(y = avg_income / 1000, color = "Average Income (in thousands)"), size = 3) +  # Points for average income
  scale_y_continuous(sec.axis = sec_axis(~.*1000, name = "Average Income")) +  # Secondary y-axis for income in thousands
  labs(
    title = "Financial Health Analysis",  # Title of the plot
    x = "Financial Health Score",  # X-axis label
    y = "Count of Users",  # Primary Y-axis label
    fill = "Metric",  # Legend title for fill color
    color = "Metric"  # Legend title for line color
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +  # Minimal theme for the plot
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Count of Users" = "lightblue")) +  # Custom color for user count bars
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Average Income (in thousands)" = "darkorange"))  # Custom color for income line

# Clean the 'credit_limit' column by removing dollar signs and converting to numeric
combined_data$credit_limit <- as.numeric(gsub("\\$", "", combined_data$credit_limit))

# Convert relevant columns to factor type for categorical analysis

combined_data$card_brand <- as.factor(combined_data$card_brand)
combined_data$card_type <- as.factor(combined_data$card_type)

# Fit a linear regression model to predict yearly income based on several predictors
model <- lm(yearly_income ~ current_age + credit_score + debt_to_income + num_credit_cards + credit_limit, data = combined_data)

# Display the summary of the regression model to see coefficients and statistics
summary(model)

# Summarize card brand and type preferences by gender
gender_preferences <- combined_data %>%
  group_by(gender, card_brand, card_type) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count) * 100)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'gender', 'card_brand'. You can override
## using the `.groups` argument.
# Print the gender preferences summary
print(gender_preferences)
